Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: Short version: it's what's known as a "loss leader". This is when a store intentionally sells a product for less than what it costs them to put it on the shelf in order to attract customers who will usually buy something else while they're there. Grocery stores do this with milk.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment:
It's no different conceptually then what Winco does with their fried chicken. They place the section in a section of the store that makes it clear you walk by as much items as possible, to entice potential additional purchases. And in Wincos case, they keep their prices low by requiring certain fried chicken sets (we add these drums and wings for example always at a specific ratio) and to minimize waste as well. They also sell their fried chicken cold for a often more expensive price. 
Just wanted to bring it up because I considered similar context, and also I know there's other viewers out there that go to Winco Foods that dont often consider that factor in the northwest.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken
Comment: In other words, the chicken price and the demand for those chickens have hit equilibrium, which is when the market price of quantity of goods supplied is equal to the quantity of goods demanded at said price. This is the point at which the demand and supply curves in the market intersect, and it's also where profit is maximized. That's why it's not always better to raise prices or lower them.

Title: This Is Why Costco Only Charges $5 For A Rotisserie Chicken

Title: Removing Meat from a Costco Rotisserie Chicken
Comment:
Thank You for showing me how to not spend 30 minutes deboning a chicken!  

I save the debris (skin, bones, and juice in the container) as the start for a chicken and sausage gumbo by placing it into a pot, adding enough water (or boxed chicken stock) to cover it and simmer for 30+ minutes.  Pour the debris and liquid through a fine mesh strainer, placed over a large measuring cup.  Discard the debris, let the liquid cool, cover, and place in the fridge for a few hours or overnight and the next day skim the fat from the top.  At this point I either freeze the liquid or add it to my roux, along with the reserved chicken meat and continue cooking my gumbo.

Title: The Big Problem Costco Shoppers Are Currently Having With Their Rotisserie Chickens
Comment: I never bought Costco's rotisserie chicken, but this whole topic made me curious, so I bought one today. I can definitely understand where people are coming from. There was subtle chemical taste, which may not be noticed by most people. I also noticed that there was a part of the leg that was particularly strong in chemical taste. Title: The Big Problem Costco Shoppers Are Currently Having With Their Rotisserie Chickens
Comment: There is a chemical taste I have been noticing in foods of all types for over forty years. This taste is due to a disinfectant that is used to clean equipment and preparation surfaces, and I don't believe it is chlorine bleach. They wipe down surfaces with this stuff, whatever it is, then fail to rinse or wipe down with plain water. A soft-serve ice cream place that I once frequented made a batch without rinsing the cleaner out of the equipment. It was uneatable. I threw it away, and never went back. Some places like Taco Bell and pizza joints slide the food down the stainless steel counter, and the food picks-up the off taste if cleaning was improperly done. Food service workers may have even been told they don't need to rinse after using this product. A quick look at food service disinfectants sold on Amazon show that they brag about not needing rinsing. Sure, if you don't mind your food tasting like disinfectant.

Hyperinsulinemia activates angiotensin II rennin causes kidneys to increase blood pressure. Electrolytes imbalance of magnesium and potassium will result in hypertension as well. But it's much easier to blame sodium than address the real cause.

Comment:
I caught a quick glimpse of the Prime ribeye steak you picked up and noticed it was missing the spinalis and then you picked up the spinalis and said it was your favorite cut of meat. The Costcos in my area (Central Valley California-Stockton, Modesto, Manteca) started removing the spinalis just from the prime ribeye (not from the Choice) about a year ago and began selling them separately at a higher price (now they are both the same price). (They use to have both the intact prime ribeye and spinalis before that but they discontinued the spinalis for awhile and later resorted to just getting the spinalis from the prime ribeyes they were selling. A disservice to prime ribeye fans who relish the spinalis part of the ribeye.) 

I found this to be such a conniving, deceitful, practice (when it was priced higher than the ribeye) that I stopped buying the prime ribeye altogether. Now, with the pandemic, both prime ribeyes and spinalis meat are just over the top at about $22/lbs. in my area so buying them isn't really in the best interest of my pocket book when I can get it at my local steak restaurants for about the same price and with loads of side dishes.

I wonder which Costco you were at (?) because I've seen other recent Costco shopping videos that still sell the prime ribeye intact, without stealing the spinalis off of them to be sold separately. This led me to believe they were just doing it at the lesser affluent cities because the videos that showed intact ribeyes were in more influential cities.

Title: Shopping At Costco For Meat & Seafood - What To Buy & Avoid
Comment: Regarding scallops and shrimp. Most often they are full of sodium tripolyphosphate (STP or STPP), which is a salt that adheres itself to the cells causing them to retain water. It's used by the food industry to add weight to the food for more profit. It cannot be washed out, and can only be removed by heating, hence the white glue-like ooze that comes out of seafood when cooked. It's hard to find seafood without STP. I've checked Costo's shrimp and it's on the label. Check the unpeeled, as they sometimes don't have it but the peeled will most often. Also, scallops are known as "wet" (with STPP) or "Dry" (without STPP)...so obviously dry is best and will sear in a pan instead of steam.

Comment:
I don't have a Costco in my town, but we do have a Sam's Club and I've been thinking about getting a membership off and on.. are the prices for meat about the same or are the two large/bulk department grocery stores similar in lower prices than other standard grocery stores?
Also, those prime steaks that said blade tenderized on the label haven't been passed through a mechanical tenderizer. If they had they would be thinned out and flattened out and would have tons of small shallow poke holes throughout them. I worked in a grocery store meat market with a cutting room where we tenderized meats through the machine, so yeah... You'd definitely know if a cut has been tenderized through the machine or with a mallet. My guess is the description/handling section of those label are outdated with the only change made to them being the designation of the cut and the price per pound, which is pretty common with grocery store labels.

Comment: Of note about "organic" chicken. The term "organic" being owned by the US government is subject to changes and revisions. The word "organic" is a political term with it's definition being a constant moving target. There is little integrity in it.

Comment:
Sorry Bobby, the wild caught previously salmon, with the label "Product of USA" is NOT an American product at.  It is a foreign resource packaged in the US only.  That labeling appears on any & all foreign meat & fish products under the Obama administration in 2015.  Foreign raw meats became avail in the US in his first administration in 2009. Before 2009 no meat or fish sold raw was anything other than US raised, processed & packaged in the US.
I highly suspect a large portion of Costco meats are from foreign countries, which is why US meat purveyors are marketing their brand labels, look for USDA, not "Product of USA".

Wait one minute:)...Grass fed beef does not taste good.   Plus grass is different in  different regions of the country so you can not  compare how it will even taste. It takes much longer for cattle to gain weight for marbling on grass.  Grain fed beef tastes better and is more expensive to feed the cattle  than grass. Grain and feed companies have scientists getting the best nutrition to the animals.   Purina Animal Nutrition Research farm ,  science leader in this field who studies all the nutrition going into the cattle.   Who is researching the grass?  Is that grass dry or healthy. Is it sprayed , does it has a fungus, what is its quality? 
Deer hunters go to states with great foliage and  field corn in fields because the meat tastes better.  Taste a hamburger in Hawaii where most are grass fed to a juicy burger from cattle raised with excellent nutrition fed in Iowa. 
Why so many people are pulled into the grass fed idea is an example how gullible we are under good marketing or a fad mentality. I just need to see scientific evidence that grass is better!

Title: Shopping At Costco For Meat & Seafood - What To Buy & Avoid
Comment: "Certified Humanin" is just another BS marketing term like “Cage Free”, “Free Range”, etc. You think you’re getting a bird that spent its life, as un-naturally short as it is, running around in the grass in the sunshine being a bird. Not so much. If it is feed a vegetarian diet, it’s not the complete diet the bird was designed to eat. Part of the natural diet for these birds are bugs, worms, etc. The only way you are going to get a bird that was raised the way nature intended is to raise your own, or get it from a local farmer that you can visit to verify you’re getting a bird raised the way you think it is raised. If the price is cheap, it’s not what you think no matter what it says. Large scale farmers can’t afford the costs of raising birds out doors in the conditions that are more natural for it. They simple don’t get that much money for their products. If you’re buying at a large chain store, you’re getting a bird raised as cheaply as possible. As for “Farm” raised seafood. No matter what they say, it’s not sustainable. The dirty little secret they don’t tell you is the oceans are rapped for all the small fish they can get to feed these farms. Fish are designed to eat other fish smaller than they are. Not grains, but fish. I just hate seeing people taken advantage of with marketing BS! Don’t fall for it.

Title: Shopping At Costco For Meat & Seafood - What To Buy & Avoid
Comment:
1.)  Regardless of whether you shop at Costco or a fish market, there is no salmon that is currently safe.  Farm raised Salmon is the worst with mushy meat and supposedly wild caught salmon is contaminated with what is flowing from Fukushima.  Almost all sea food choices at Costco are a no no.  There is only one fish they have that is not often carried and that is New Zealand Hoki.  AND, don't ever buy already breaded fish or meat, because you have no idea what type of contamination their coatings have covered up.
2.)  No "Organic Chicken" is not better, because the term is falsely applied, because the word "organic" doesn't mean shit when it comes to chicken.  The best you could hope for is that maybe term "Organic" means they were raised without antibiotics.  I'm 73 and have been eating Foster Farms chicken for over 50 years and have suffered no issue from it.  Actually do some research on what organic means to the chicken industry.  It is actually a bull shit term used to confuse the buyer into thinking it is more healthy than are Foster Farms chicken.  Also chicken legs at $1.79 per pound is so over the top I will not buy them, I don't care if that label says organic or not.  Why, because I used to be a meat cutter and I know what meat should cost.
3.)  I am only 1/4 the way through the video and have opted to stop.  Apparently this guy is being paid by Costco because he is a little too effusive about the supposed good pricing, and I don't want to have to tell you the truth about what else he says about the different grades of beef, or pork.  The Lamb Costco carries taste like crap and is imported of course and was more than likely previously frozen.  If you want a good price on your chicken purchase one of Costco's already cooked birds, they are the best and are only about $5.00 each which is a steal.
I'm out of here.

Title: Shopping At Costco For Meat & Seafood - What To Buy & Avoid
Comment:
When salmon gets close to aging limit, it goes on sale, like all other perishables.  Who made this guy an expert?  Ground turkey used to be from thigh meat, now it comes from comminuted meat.  It all is horrible (ever notice that ground turkey is watery to the touch in the container as well as in raw state out of the package, it is the mechanical deboning process that does that.  there is no muscle striation to be gathered by comminuting.  Also, get educated man.  That logo for Certified Humane (on first package) is not the gold standard program by HFAC, it is not correct verbiage, not a 3rd party verified program.  The second call out is.

Dude, Australian, New Zealand lamb just plain sucks.  Go for the USDA Spring Fed Lamb,  domestic lamb cannot be beat.  Not gamy at all.

Jacard is not used in all states because according to some local food safety laws, by using a Jacard machine the meat must be sold as non-intact muscle.  If it is cooked in a restaurant it needs to be cooked to over 160 degrees.  The reason they are Jacarding at all is that they do not age their meat so without the benefit of wet aging, the connective tissue and natural enzymatic breakdown of the muscle is not given time to make more tender, hence Jacarding.  And you are greatly mistake if you think that Grading has anything to do with tenderness.  Scientific fact, read CSU documentation on aging protocols.  You can cook to any temp you want but for liability concerns, they are going to all out cooking times.  You need to get educated on ingredient statements.

Organic does not mean it is a product of the USA, it just means that the meat was verified to be Organic.  You should be an advocate for reinstating the COOL packaging requirement that went out the window during Obama era.  Consumers don't know much and this was an end around for Canadian beef (nearly 100% barley fed) and Mexican beef (which I call poison resulting form the high levels of beta agonists used in the feed).

Get educated and be of service to your subscribers, you could do with a real life walk through Costco by someone who can help educate you so you can pass it on.  Foodie; over informed, under educated.

Title: Shopping At Costco For Meat & Seafood - What To Buy & Avoid
Comment: The focus on organic and non-GMO foods is a little overstated I think. Studies have not confirmed that livestock raised with genetically engineered feed have any statistically significant health effects on human beings. Also, organic farming, despite popular belief is worse for the environment. According to a 2018 study by Chalmers University of Technology in Sweden, it was discovered that when all factors were taken into account the farming of organic peas versus non-organic peas resulted in an approximately 50% jump in climate impact. This is primarily due to the decreased amount of organic crop that can be grown per hectare. Long story short, organic is not necessarily better and GMOs have not proven to pose any health risk to date.

Title: Shopping At Costco For Meat & Seafood - What To Buy & Avoid
Comment: There is no data to indicate that consumption of GMOs is bad for human health. GMOs have undergone more detailed evaluation than any other group of plants that we consume. In almost all cases, GMOs differ from a conventional plant by the addition of just one or two genes that produce one or two new proteins. The origin and function of these proteins are well understood. For example, the proteins are studied to make sure they do not have any characteristics that are likely to cause allergic reactions. The National Academy for Science, the United States’ number one source for independent, objective advice to the nation on matters of science and technology, concluded that GMOs are safe for human health. The same conclusion has been reached by a large number of prestigious health and science organizations from around the world. In addition, over the two decades that GMOs have been on the market, there have been no occurrences of health issues due to genetically modified organisms.

Title: Shopping At Costco For Meat & Seafood - What To Buy & Avoid
Comment:
If you want excellent flavor and tenderness, then buy American grown lamb, Australian and New Zealand lamb have that slight "gamy" taste and isn't as tender, that's the difference between grain fed and grass fed. 
 
Much the same applies to beef, while grass fed beef is very lean, it's the fat content (marbling) of the grain fed cows that give it tenderness, juiciness, and most importantly taste. As for chicken, its a personal choice, I have no problem eating chicken that is non organic and GMO grain fed (there is zero scientific evidence that GMO feed is harmful to chickens or their meat is to consume by humans). I do prefer the breeds of meat chickens (called broilers in the chicken industry) that was commonly sold in the US in the mid 1980s and before, then commercial chicken growers switched over to the Conish Cross breed of chickens because they grow very big, very quickly, making them the most profitable. Cornish Crosses don't really taste like anything, they are close to being flavorless. 

 I do stay away from "pumped" chicken, that is chicken that is injected with sodium phosphate (salt compounds) solution to retain water and juiciness. Again, this is done for profitability (known as "value added" in the chicken processing industry). While no evidence that sodium phosphate is harmful to humans in small quantities (unless you have hypertension), it is sometimes used in medicine as a laxative.

No chicken sold in the US is GMO or given is growth hormones, It's use is strictly forbidden by the FDA and USDA since the 1950s. Some brands of chicken put "Free of Growth Hormones" on their labels, they're just playing upon consumer fears in their marketing, marketing is of course, full of buzzwords, they often play upon trends and the fears of uneducated consumers.

Comment:
It does take longer to get 100% grass fed but it’s not more expensive, if you have land the cheapest way you can raise a cow is 100% grass fed and if you rotate your pastures you get rid of parasites and a lot of the pests and pretty much never have to give them antibiotics or hormones because they’re healthy, it does take longer but it’s free, you buy a baby cow and you put it out in your pasture and make sure it gets water and rotate from pasture to pasture to keep the parasites under control and that’s all you do you don’t ever have to buy it feed of any kind.  I lived in Tennessee that was pretty much how all the cows were raised, and now with all the supply chain ridiculousness going on people will probably need to start looking to local farms and processors to get meet regularly. The stores still have it from time to time but the price is going up and a lot of the times I go to the store and they’re just out. 

Another thing with the blade cut meat, one of the problems is during the pandemic they close processing plants down and sort of attacked the meat industry and you had a lot of farmers having to make the decision what to do with their cows when they went past processing age, one they were forced to sell off to The large factory processors or start processing themselves in places where it became political and the processors were shut down.  They probably started blade cutting them because they weren’t as tender and we’re older because this went on for several months and is starting again.  I noticed for a long time that beef got very tough and almost an edible, even the more expensive cuts that were marveled well because it was older Beef that should’ve been processed much earlier.  Now I’m not sure what’s happening, I know that small farms and companies like butcher block and those that ship from local processors are picking up in business as the stores don’t have all the stuff readily available in a lot of places but it will be interesting to see where all of this leads. :/   What I suggest is that people load up on it when they find the sales and places like Aldi‘s and Costco and get as much as they can store or freeze now because they may just be facing times ahead when they just can’t get food supplied properly because our government is run by a bunch of clowns.  :/

Comment: It’s kinda funny to see you’re endorsing grass finished beef but then again liking the usda prime beef. It’s a bit hypocritical wouldn’t you say ? So far it’s not proven that grass finished beef are healthier than grain finished beef . Grass finished beef doesn’t normally come to grading criteria cuz it doesn’t get that high quality to be graded. Of course if any feedlot feeding gmo grain to the cattle then that’s not good but here in Australia our top beef producers and feedlots never use gmo grain . Because of these clueless advertisements about grass finished beef we’re producing way less prime quality beef . I saw you bobby making a video about Japanese wagyu , the irony is you like wagyu but that wagyu is been eating grain it’s entire life . So please don’t follow what the supermarket tells you rather guide your followers with scientific evidences . The purpose of feedlot isn’t quickly achieve targeted weight gain of the animal, rather most of the time it’s to achieve the targeted quality . Without finishing the steers on grain based diet we can never get prime quality beef . Every harvested steer eats grass at least 70 to 80% of its life, it’s the last 100 to 200 days that either it’s finished on grain or grass . Title: Shopping At Costco For Meat & Seafood - What To Buy & Avoid
Comment: First time viewer. This guy seems to know a lot about meat, and has many good suggestions, but that said, he falls for all the psuedo-science marketing. He is correct, regarding the poor farming practices for the seafood, but he doesnt mention that wild-caught often can have worms/parasites. Not a problem if you cook it through, but dont use it for a poke bowl. Furthermore, there's nothing wrong with GMO - show me any legit science study that supports non-GMO - its a complete marketing scam. You are throwing out your money if you pay a penny extra for it. Same as those certified animal treatment labels. Same chickens can wind up in either bag. Don't take my word for it, or his word to the contrary - be skeptical - and research yourself. Organic farming (which does use chemicals and pesticides contrary to the marketing spin) and non-GMO products waste farmland and are not sustainable. Then he points to big words like "carrageenan" and others - scary stuff unless you know that "carrageenan" is vegan gelatin that comes from edible seaweed. And its not a filler (as he says) - its in the SEASONING, the last ingredient, which is the least ingredient. I'm not going to cover all the ingredient BS he's ignorantly spewing, else I'll end up writing a book. And lastly, he is scaring people away from Costco steaks because of the "blade tenderized" when there is a simple solution. Sous Vide your steak and no worries. The extended low-temp (129) cooking time of sous vide will kill dangerous bacteria, even in the center of the meat, yet the relatively short sous vide times for prime steaks (60-90m) allows for sous vide without any special equipment - just a small ice chest, a ziplock bag, and a thermometer. Enjoy your next informed Costco visit :)
